could be due to the longer $\pi$-conjugation of the sensitizing dye and lower electronic band gap when compared to dye $\mathbf{5 a}$.

To enhance the efficiency of the DSSCs sensitized with dyes $\mathbf{5 a}-\mathbf{b}$ and $7 \mathbf{c}$, we used coadsorption with DCA. Bile acids such as DCA and chenodeoxycholic acid are able to improve the efficiency of the cells because of the reduction of dye aggregation on the surface of $\mathrm{TiO}_{2}$, suppressing dark current and improving electron lifetime. 25,

The photovoltaic response of the cells with dyes $5 \mathbf{a}$ and $7 \mathbf{c}$ was increased slightly by the addition of DCA as the coadsorbent (from $2.98$ to $3.22 \%$ for dye $5 \mathbf{a}$ and from $0.72$ to $0.79 \%$ for dye $7 \mathrm{c}$ ), whereas the efficiency of the cell with dye 5b improved significantly-from $3.01$ to $5.10 \%$. It can be seen from Table 4 and Figure 2 that the addition of DCA does not affect $V_{\mathrm{OC}}$ of the cells based on dyes $\mathbf{5 a}$ and $7 \mathbf{c}$-the variations are within the statistical deviation. The slight enhancement of the performance of these cells is due to the improvement of the FF via suppressing the dark current. At the same time, for dye $\mathbf{5 b}$, coadsorption of DCA leads to noticeable increase of $V_{\mathrm{OC}}$.

